Introduction

This report provides an mini exploration of differences in juvenile snowshoe hare trap counts and weights from 1999-2012 in Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest in Interior Alaska (Kielland et al.2017). This capture-recapture study explores the snowshoe hare, which is a keystone prey species in the northern boreal forests in 3 different sites (Black Spruce, Mature and Riparian) (Kielland et al.2017). This report first explores the juvenile snowshoe hare trap counts annually from 1998 to 2012. Then explores the juvenile snowshoe hare weights by sex and site. Followed by a more focused comparison of weights between male and female juvenile hares. Lastly, explores the relationship between juvenile weights and hind foot length.

Data and anyalses

The data on snowshoe hares was collected by capture-recapture by Dr.Knut Kielland and colleagues at the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest in Fairbanks, Alaska (Kielland et al.2017). The data contain 3,197 observations of snowshoe hares, collected from 1999-2012 over three sites (Black Spruce, Mature and Riparian). Variables of consideration are hare age, sex, trapping date, trapping site, weight and hindfoot length. Exploratory visualizations and decriptive statistics are found for these variables. Juvenile weights (grams) and hind foot lengths (millimeters) are compared by two-sample t-test using a significance level (\(\alpha\)) of 0.05 and differences between groups are described by Cohens d effect size. The relationship between weight and hind foot length is explored by a linear model (All analyses are in R version 4.0.2 using RStudio version 1.4.1717).

Juvenile hare initial investigation

Section 1: Annual juvenile hare trap counts

Figure 1: Counts of juvenile hare trappings during each year of the study from 1998 to 2012 in the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest. The trap counts peak in 1999 at 126 hares data from Kielland et al.(2017).

Figure 1 takeaways

There is a general trend of decreasing counts of juvenile hare trappings from 1999-2012, there is a large spread of annual juvenile hare trap counts, ranging from 2 to 126. The mean count of juvenile hares trapped annually is 31.5 and median is 18.5. The changes from year to year show no consistent trend, other than a large drop after the maximum count year in 1999, this could be due to the fact that these are absolute counts and are impacted by the effort of researchers. I would suggest standardizing the juvenile hare population by randomly selecting uniform sample sizes for each year.

Juvenile hare weights and descriptive statistics

There is a visible difference in sample sizes of juvenile hares between sites. The Riparian site has the largest sample size of weights for male (110), female (129) and unknown (7) juvenile hares, and the Black Spruce site has the fewest counts of weights for males (13), females (35) and unknown 1. The central tendency (mean) of female weights is below male weights at each site although there is a large spread (standard deviation), for Riparian females (824.15 255.04; mean 1 standard deviation) compared to males (929.27 349.17). The biggest take away is that the large differences in sample size (n) and large standard deviations which impact the visible trends.

Section 3: Juvenile weight comparison (male & female snowshoe hares)

Table 2: Descriptive statistics (mean, median, standard deviation and sample size) of juvenile weights (g) for male and femal snowshoe hares
Sex Mean (g) Median (g) Standard deviation (g) Sample size
Female 855.4 825 292.3 200
Male 945.9 990 333.2 163

Table 2 takeaways

On average male juvenile hares weigh more than females (945.86 333.22 and 855.39333.22 g, respectively; mean 1 standard deviation). While the absolute difference in mean weight is 90.47g ( a 10.05 % difference), the difference in means is significant (Welchs two-sample t-test: t(325.02) = 2.71, p < 0.001), and the effect size is small (Cohens d = 0.29). This indicated that further investigation would need to be done to identify a significant difference in the mean weights between these two sample means.

Section 4: Relationship between juvenile weight & hind foot length

Figure 3: Relationship between juvenile hare weight (g) and hind food length (mm). Points indicate individual hare measurements. Linear model summary: \(\beta\)1 = 9.52 g/mm, p < 0.001, R2 = 0.3, Pearsons r = 0.55. Based on the R2 value on 30% of variance in hare weights can be explained by hind foot length and Pearsons r value describes medium positive relationship between the two variables. Additionally, a linear regression assumes homoskedasticity of data, and the plot above lends concern to this assumption as the data appears heteroskedastic. Data: Kielland et al.(2017).

Summary

Exploratory data analysis reveals the following initial findings:

  • The differences in sample sizes between years and sites make it difficult to draw definitive conclusions about the data.

  • Given a small to moderate effect size and p value < 0.01, we cannot reject the null hypothesis: that male and female sample populations are from populations with the same mean weight.

  • The lack of homoskedasticity in the comparison of hare weight and hind foot length suggest that the regression model may need to include additional predictor variables to explain the performance of the dependent variable.
